removed k argument, it is now inferred from the number of leading commas in the first line of the kmer file. kmer_file default setting is no longer the W303 3mer distribution. If no kmer file is provided, the kmer distribution is constructed from the target gc content, with k=1.

corrected bug when there was missing flanking sequences in get_profile_mutations, i.e. no flanks or flanks to short. Added gctol argument to not penalize GCs closer than gctol to the target. Made the random window of mutations to scan per step be selected using a step of nmut_step // 4, to this end the helper function maxstep_linspace was added. Changed all direct uses of np.random, including seeding, by instances of numpy random generator objects. Changed config file format, by putting all parameters in the json portion.
changed all direct uses of np.random to have a numpy Random Generator object be instantiated, also added som type hints

debugged functional version, added new features: an argument nmut_step for the maximum number of mutations to consider at each step; an argument patience for an early stopping procedure if the energy hasnâ€™t improved over given amount of step; the argumentmut_batch_size replaces pos_batch_size, it represents the number of mutated sequences to test at once and is scaled down depending on number of sequences and sequence length to allow same value being used; get_profile_chunk had a bug corrected when a chunk had length 1, squeeze would remove the first dimension as well, it now only performs squeeze on the last axis; get_profile_mutations accepts cur_indices as 1D or 2D; time is displayed using datetime, making it more readable.
changed sliding_GC to output a value even if n is larger than the sequence length

new version of kMC_sequence_design, still untested. Major features include get_profile_mutations, a function allowing to predict only on windows where the mutation has an effect and update the initial preditions. all_mutations has been optimised save memory when mutations are required only at specific positions, this is coupled with mutations performed and evaluated in batches, to save memory again. GC_energy has been changed to compute a sliding GC over the sequence and then take its rmse relative to the target, this allows for local control of GC content. Other than that code has been reworked to include get_pred_start_and_stop and pad_sequences functions, the first to extract pred_start and pred_stop from model output type (winsize, head_interval, middle) and the second to add the flanking sequences. seen_bases has been renamed to bases_occs. Type hints have been added to each function. There are 2 new arguments: gc_constrlen for the length over which the sliding GC should be computed, and pos_batch_size, for the number of mutation positions that are to be performed at once.
updated calls to sliding_GC, because sliding_GC considers tokens as default

added slicer_on_axis function to allow taking slices of an array along a given axis, this function is used to generalize moving_sum to allow the axis parameter (it previously only worked for axis=0). Added a test function for moving_sum. Updated sliding_GC to allow both tokens or one-hots as input, and for tokens to allow an axis parameter over which to compute the sliding GC. Added type hints on new functions and on kmer_counts.

changes:
clip_to_nonzero_min creates a copy by default, not modifying input array inplace. The argument copy was added to control this behavior. Also a docstring was added.
integer_histogram_sample was changed by splitting part of the code into another function, and it now optionnaly returns the complement as well with the new argument return_complement.

New functions:
integer_histogram_serie_sample is a version of a histogram sample but on pandas Series, it can be faster than integer_histogram_sample when the number of unique values isn't to big with respect to the total count.
zero_to_epsilon is an alternative to clip_to_nonzero_min, which instead changes the zero values to the numpy epsilon of that dtype.
nan_pearson is a version of pearson which works for arrays with nans. However I recommend using nan_compress and the regular pearson function.
nan_compress takes as input a list of arrays and returns them without the indices where at least one of them had a nan.
